<p></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Composition">Composition</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Piano_Sonata_No._5_(Scriabin)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Composition">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lausanne--Avenue-Harpe-14.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Lausanne--Avenue-Harpe-14.jpg/250px-Lausanne--Avenue-Harpe-14.jpg" width="250" height="158" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Lausanne--Avenue-Harpe-14.jpg/375px-Lausanne--Avenue-Harpe-14.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Lausanne--Avenue-Harpe-14.jpg/500px-Lausanne--Avenue-Harpe-14.jpg 2x" data-file-width="740" data-file-height="467" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lausanne--Avenue-Harpe-14.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Avenue de la Harpe 14, Lausanne, Switzerland. Scriabin lived in that building between 1907 and 1908. Here he revised the score of his <i>Po√®me de l'Extase</i> and composed his Fifth Piano Sonata.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:132px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Cover--RMV.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Cover--RMV.png/130px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Cover--RMV.png" width="130" height="163" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Cover--RMV.png/195px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Cover--RMV.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Cover--RMV.png/260px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Cover--RMV.png 2x" data-file-width="804" data-file-height="1010" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Cover--RMV.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Cover page of one of the first editions of the work. <a href="/wiki/Serge_Koussevitzky" title="Serge Koussevitzky">Russische Musikverlag</a>, 1910. The engraving is by <a href="/wiki/Ivan_Bilibin" title="Ivan Bilibin">Ivan Bilibin</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>After finishing his symphonic poem <a href="/wiki/The_Poem_of_Ecstasy" title="The Poem of Ecstasy"><i>Le Po√®me de l'Extase</i>, Op.54</a>, Scriabin did not feel comfortable living in <a href="/wiki/Paris" title="Paris">Paris</a>. In early September 1907 he wrote:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>"Life is fearfully expensive, and the climate is rotten. The air in the areas where we could find an apartment big enough for us at a reasonable price is frightful [...] you cannot make any noise. You have to wear house slippers after 10 at night."<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Scriabin decided to go to live in Lausanne with his pregnant wife Tatyana,<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>nb 1<span>]</span></a></sup> since he found the place to be cheaper, quieter, and healthier, and only 7 hours away from Paris. Also, he had his music being printed there, as he had recently broken his long-term partnership with publisher <a href="/wiki/Mitrofan_Belyayev" title="Mitrofan Belyayev">M.P. Belaieff</a> due to financial discrepancies.<sup id="cite_ref-fau_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fau-3"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In his new peaceful household in <i>Edifice C Place de la Harpe</i>,<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>nb 2<span>]</span></a></sup> Scriabin could play the piano without fear of complaints from neighbours, and soon began to compose again, alongside the revisions he was making to the score of <i>Le Po√®me</i>. On 8 December, Tatyana wrote to a friend:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>"We go out a little, having caught up on our sleep. We begin to look normal again. Sasha even has begun to compose - 5th Sonata!!! I cannot believe my ears. It is incredible! That sonata pours from him like a fountain. Everything you have heard up to now is as nothing. You cannot even tell it is a sonata. Nothing compares to it. He has played it through several times, and all he has to do is to write it down [...]."<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
</blockquote>
<p>On late December, Scriabin wrote to Morozova about the imminent completion of his new work:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>"The Poem of Ecstasy took much of my strength and taxed my patience. [...] Today I have almost finished my 5th Sonata. It is a big poem for piano and I deem it the best composition I have ever written. I do not know by what miracle I accomplished it [...]."<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Although the actual writing took only six days, from 8 to 14 December 1907, some ideas had been conceived much earlier. The initial nine bars of the first theme of the exposition, <i>Presto con allegrezza</i> <sup>(mm. 47 ff.)</sup>, can be found in a notebook from 1905-1906, when Scriabin was in Chicago.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>nb 3<span>]</span></a></sup> Another notebook from 1906 contains the <i>Imperioso</i> theme <sup>(mm. 96 ff.)</sup>, while elements from the <i>Meno vivo</i> <sup>(mm. 120 ff.)</sup> can also be made out, as well as sketched-out passages for a few other sections.<sup id="cite_ref-fau_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fau-3"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-hen_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hen-8"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9"><span>[</span>nb 4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Scriabin included an epigraph to this sonata, extracted from his essay <i>Le Po√®me de l'Extase</i>:<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10"><span>[</span>nb 5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table class="multicol" role="presentation" style="border-collapse: collapse; padding: 0; border: 0; background:transparent; width:100%;">
<tr>
<td style="width: 33.33%;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;">
<dl>
<dd><b>Original Russian text</b></dd>
<dd><i>–Ø –∫ –∂–∏–∑–Ω–∏ –ø—Ä–∏–∑—ã–≤–∞—é –≤–∞—Å, —Å–∫—Ä—ã—Ç—ã–µ —Å—Ç—Ä–µ–º–ª–µ–Ω—å—è!</i></dd>
<dd><i>–í—ã, —É—Ç–æ–Ω—É–≤—à–∏–µ –≤ —Ç–µ–º–Ω—ã—Ö –≥–ª—É–±–∏–Ω–∞—Ö</i></dd>
<dd><i>–î—É—Ö–∞ —Ç–≤–æ—Ä—è—â–µ–≥–æ, –≤—ã, –±–æ—è–∑–ª–∏–≤—ã–µ</i></dd>
<dd><i>–ñ–∏–∑–Ω–∏ –∑–∞—Ä–æ–¥—ã—à–∏, –≤–∞–º –¥–µ—Ä–∑–Ω–æ–≤–µ–Ω—å–µ –ø—Ä–∏–Ω–æ—à—É!</i></dd>
</dl>
</td>
<td style="width: 33.33%;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;">
<dl>
<dd><b>Original French translation</b></dd>
<dd><i>Je vous appelle √† la vie, √¥ forces mysterieuses!</i></dd>
<dd><i>Noy√©es dans les obscures profondeurs</i></dd>
<dd><i>De l‚Äôesprit cr√©ateur, craintives</i></dd>
<dd><i>Ebauches de vie, √† vous j‚Äôapporte l‚Äôaudace!</i></dd>
</dl>
</td>
<td style="width: 33.33%;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;">
<dl>
<dd><b>English translation</b></dd>
<dd><i>I call you to life, oh mysterious forces!</i></dd>
<dd><i>Drowned in the obscure depths</i></dd>
<dd><i>Of the creative spirit, timid</i></dd>
<dd><i>Shadows of life, to you I bring audacity!</i><sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup></dd>
</dl>
</td>
<td style="width: 33.33%;text-align:left;vertical-align:top;"></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>Five months after its completion, Scriabin published the work himself in Lausanne, producing an edition with 300 copies.<sup id="cite_ref-fau_3-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fau-3"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> He later gave the autograph as a present to his pupil <a href="/wiki/Alfred_La_Libert%C3%A9" title="Alfred La Libert√©">Alfred La Libert√©</a>. In 1971 the pianist‚Äôs widow gave the manuscript, along with various other documents, to the Scriabin Museum.<sup id="cite_ref-hen_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hen-8"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The work was premiered on 18 November 1908 in <a href="/wiki/Moscow" title="Moscow">Moscow</a> by pianist <a href="/w/index.php?title=Mark_Meitschik&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Mark Meitschik (page does not exist)">Mark Meitschik</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-fau_3-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fau-3"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Structure">Structure</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Piano_Sonata_No._5_(Scriabin)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Structure">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>The piece is written in <a href="/wiki/Sonata_form" title="Sonata form">sonata form</a><sup id="cite_ref-samson_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-samson-12"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup> with an introduction. The structure of the work is described in the table below:</p>
<table border="1" cellpadding="5" align="center" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<th style="background: #efefef;">Section</th>
<th style="background: #efefef;">Subsection</th>
<th style="background: #efefef;">Excerpt</th>
<th style="background: #efefef;">mm.</th>
<th style="background: #efefef;">Description</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="2">Introduction</td>
<td>1</td>
<td>
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning.png/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning.png" width="420" height="112" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning.png/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning.png/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning.png 2x" data-file-width="1140" data-file-height="305" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 1-3. <i>Allegro impetuoso</i> theme. All the notes belong to a diatonic scale, but there is no clearly discernible tonality.</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>1-12</td>
<td>The sonata begins with an introduction. Its first part consists of an agitated theme, marked <i>allegro-impetuoso-con stravaganza</i>. It features trills and glissandos, and ends in an agitated ascending rush followed by a pause.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning2.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning2.png/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning2.png" width="420" height="208" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning2.png/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning2.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning2.png/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning2.png 2x" data-file-width="1183" data-file-height="586" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Beginning2.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 13-24. <i>Languido</i> theme. All the harmonies are related to an F<span class="music-symbol" style="font-family: Arial Unicode MS, Lucida Sans Unicode;">‚ôØ</span>-dominant chord.</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>13-46</td>
<td>A second theme follows at m. 13, marked <i>languido</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13"><span>[</span>nb 6<span>]</span></a></sup></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="4">Exposition</td>
<td>First theme</td>
<td>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp1.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp1.png/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp1.png" width="420" height="190" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp1.png/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp1.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp1.png/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp1.png 2x" data-file-width="1178" data-file-height="532" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp1.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 47-53 and 68-69. <i>Presto con allegrezza</i> theme. In its first appearance it is harmonised as an <a href="/wiki/Eleventh_chord" title="Eleventh chord">dominant eleventh</a> chord. Later it is restated over a tonic pedal.</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>47-95</td>
<td>The exposition commences at m. 47. The first theme, marked <i>presto con allegrezza</i> is in F<span class="music-symbol" style="font-family: Arial Unicode MS, Lucida Sans Unicode;">‚ôØ</span> major and set in <a href="/wiki/Binary_form" title="Binary form">binary form</a>. The first half begins with a 6-bar phrase (harmonized as dominant eleventh chord) followed by the same prase transposed a fourth higher (harmonized with a C<span class="music-symbol" style="font-family: Arial Unicode MS, Lucida Sans Unicode;">‚ôØ</span> minor seventh chord). After this, a 4-bar and a derived 5-bar phrases. The second half <sup>(mm. 69 ff.)</sup> begins as A but now over a tonic pedal. After reprising the first 12 bars, a series of shorter phrases bring more agitation to the passage, leading to the transition passage.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Transition</td>
<td>
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp2.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bc/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp2.png/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp2.png" width="420" height="97" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bc/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp2.png/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp2.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bc/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp2.png/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp2.png 2x" data-file-width="1183" data-file-height="272" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp2.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 96-99. <i>Imperioso</i> and <i>sotto voce misterioso affanato</i> motifs. The first features an angular melody over an arpeggiated dominant chord. The second is built on block <a href="/wiki/French_sixth" title="French sixth" class="mw-redirect">french sixth</a> chords</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="center">
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:372px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-No5--Quasi-trombe.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fe/Scriabin--Sonata-No5--Quasi-trombe.PNG/370px-Scriabin--Sonata-No5--Quasi-trombe.PNG" width="370" height="95" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fe/Scriabin--Sonata-No5--Quasi-trombe.PNG/555px-Scriabin--Sonata-No5--Quasi-trombe.PNG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fe/Scriabin--Sonata-No5--Quasi-trombe.PNG/740px-Scriabin--Sonata-No5--Quasi-trombe.PNG 2x" data-file-width="1019" data-file-height="263" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-No5--Quasi-trombe.PNG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 114-117. <i>Quasi tromba</i> motif, built on an Eb major seventh chord in first inversion. It is followed by a C-dominant ninth chord, that prepares the second theme.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>96-119</td>
<td>The transition begins at m. 96, and consists of three 2-bar motifs. It gradually moves from the initial C<span class="music-symbol" style="font-family: Arial Unicode MS, Lucida Sans Unicode;">‚ôØ</span> major tonality to the Bb major tonality of the second theme. The first motif is marked <i>imperioso</i> . The second is marked <i>sotto voce misterioso affanato</i>. These two motifs are presented alternatively three times, then, the second is prolonged and bursts in a third 2-bar motif marked <i>quasi trombe-im√®rioso</i>. A dominant ninth chord prepares the entrance of the second theme.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Second theme</td>
<td>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp3.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp3.png/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp3.png" width="420" height="193" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp3.png/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp3.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp3.png/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp3.png 2x" data-file-width="1189" data-file-height="547" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5-Exp3.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 120-124 and 134-135. <i>Meno vivo</i> theme. In its first appearance it is harmonised as a dominant chord. Later it is restated over a tonic pedal.</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>120-139</td>
<td>The second theme begins at m. 120. It is marked <i>meno mosso</i>, is in B<span class="music-symbol" style="font-family: Arial Unicode MS, Lucida Sans Unicode;">‚ô≠</span> major and also set in binary form. The first half begins with a chromatic phrase built over a dominant chord. The second <sup>(mm. 134 ff.)</sup> quotes the first but now over a tonic pedal.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Codetta</td>
<td>
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-6-Beginning.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Scriabin--Sonata-6-Beginning.png/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-6-Beginning.png" width="420" height="196" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Scriabin--Sonata-6-Beginning.png/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-6-Beginning.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Scriabin--Sonata-6-Beginning.png/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-6-Beginning.png 2x" data-file-width="1185" data-file-height="553" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-6-Beginning.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 140-148. <i>Allegro fantastico</i> motif followed by <i>presto tumultuoso esaltato</i> theme. The first features major seventh chords. The second is built on motifs from the first theme and ends in the <i>quasi tromba-imperioso</i> motif and a seventh B<span class="music-symbol" style="font-family: Arial Unicode MS, Lucida Sans Unicode;">‚ô≠</span> majortonic chord.</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>140-165</td>
<td>The codetta follows at m. 140, interrupting the second theme. It consists of three motifs. Fist, a new 2-bar motif, marked <i>allegro fantastico</i>, followed by a longer idea, marked <i>presto tumultuoso esaltato</i>, which is stated twice. It concludes with a shortened version of the trill theme transposed a major second up.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="6">Development</td>
<td>1</td>
<td>
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development1.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development1.PNG/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development1.PNG" width="420" height="99" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development1.PNG/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development1.PNG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development1.PNG/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development1.PNG 2x" data-file-width="1183" data-file-height="280" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development1.PNG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 166-171. Literal restatement of the <i>languido</i> theme transposed a major second up.</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>166-184</td>
<td>The development at m.166 begins presenting the first 17 bars of <i>languido</i> theme transposed a major second up.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td>
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development2.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development2.PNG/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development2.PNG" width="420" height="189" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development2.PNG/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development2.PNG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development2.PNG/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development2.PNG 2x" data-file-width="1173" data-file-height="527" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development2.PNG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 185-197. First theme interrupted several times by <i>imperioso</i> theme.</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>185-226</td>
<td>The development section follows with an episode featuring the first theme, which is "interrupted" several times by the <i>imperioso</i> motif.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>3</td>
<td>
<div class="center">
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development3.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development3.PNG/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development3.PNG" width="420" height="110" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development3.PNG/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development3.PNG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development3.PNG/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development3.PNG 2x" data-file-width="1019" data-file-height="268" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development3.PNG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 227-230. Passage derived from the <i>presto tumultuoso esaltato</i> theme.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="center">
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development4.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development4.PNG/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development4.PNG" width="420" height="110" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development4.PNG/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development4.PNG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development4.PNG/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development4.PNG 2x" data-file-width="1148" data-file-height="302" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development4.PNG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 247-248 and 251-252. Parodies of the trills theme and the <i>languido</i> theme.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>227-270</td>
<td>The next section features materials derived from the coda and the introduction. First, the <i>presto tumultuoso esaltato</i> is developed. The trills theme is briefly quoted<sup>(mm.247-250)</sup>. Then, the <i>languido</i> theme is mocked <sup>(mm.251 ff.)</sup>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>4</td>
<td>
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development5.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development5.png/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development5.png" width="420" height="112" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development5.png/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development5.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development5.png/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development5.png 2x" data-file-width="1173" data-file-height="312" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development5.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 271-273. Fragmentary statements of the <i>meno mosso</i> theme.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development6.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development6.png/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development6.png" width="420" height="118" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development6.png/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development6.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development6.png/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development6.png 2x" data-file-width="1173" data-file-height="329" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development6.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm. 281-284. The <i>meno mosso</i> is interrupted by the <i>allegro fantastico</i> theme twice.</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>271-288</td>
<td>At m. 271 fragments of the <i>meno mosso</i> theme appear. First, it is partly stated twice, and then, it is interruopted twice by the <i>allegro fantstico</i> theme.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>5</td>
<td>
<div class="thumb tnone">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:422px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development7.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development7.png/420px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development7.png" width="420" height="99" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development7.png/630px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development7.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development7.png/840px-Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development7.png 2x" data-file-width="1179" data-file-height="279" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scriabin--Sonata-5--Development7.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mm.289-293. Passage based on the <i>allegro fantastico</i> theme.</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
<td>289-312</td>
<td>At m. 289 the <i>allegro fantastico</i> motif succeeds over the <i>meno mosso</i> theme, and a passage built over this motif begins, creating increasing tension.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>6</td>
<td></td>
<td>313-329</td>
<td>At m. 313 the <i>allegro fantastico</i> passage burst in a climax based on the <i>meno mosso</i> theme. The four-bar phrase is stated three times, each one a fifth lower, first in D<span class="music-symbol" style="font-family: Arial Unicode MS, Lucida Sans Unicode;">‚ô≠</span> major, then in G<span class="music-symbol" style="font-family: Arial Unicode MS, Lucida Sans Unicode;">‚ô≠</span> and finally in B. However, the expected final climax is interrupted by the reexposition of the first theme in <i>pp</i>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="1">Recapitulation</td>
<td></td>
<td></td>
<td>329-400</td>
<td>The exposition (second half of the first theme, transition, second theme) is repeated note-for-note transposed a fifth down.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="1">Coda</td>
<td></td>
<td></td>
<td>401-457</td>
<td>The coda is modified so as to lead to a climatic <i>fff</i> statement of the <i>languido</i> theme, followed by the ascending rush of the first musical idea.</td>
</tr>
</table>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Harmonic_language">Harmonic language</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Piano_Sonata_No._5_(Scriabin)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Harmonic language">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<table class="metadata plainlinks ambox ambox-style ambox-Prose" role="presentation">
<tr>
<td class="mbox-image">
<div style="width:52px"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png" width="40" height="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/60px-Edit-clear.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/80px-Edit-clear.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="48" data-file-height="48" /></div>
</td>
<td class="mbox-text"><span class="mbox-text-span">This article <b>is in a list format that may be better presented using <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Prose" title="Wikipedia:Prose" class="mw-redirect">prose</a>.</b> <span class="hide-when-compact">You can help by converting this article to prose, if <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Embedded_list" title="Wikipedia:Embedded list" class="mw-redirect">appropriate</a>. <a href="/wiki/Help:Editing" title="Help:Editing">Editing help</a> is available.</span> <small><i>(April 2012)</i></small></span></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>According to Samson, unlike his later sonatas,<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14"><span>[</span>nb 7<span>]</span></a></sup> the sonata-form of this work still has some meaning to the work's tonal structure.<sup id="cite_ref-samson_12-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-samson-12"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The work does not contain any <a href="/wiki/Perfect_cadence" title="Perfect cadence" class="mw-redirect">perfect cadence</a>, nor any consonant chord.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15"><span>[</span>nb 8<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The work features one of the strange occurrences of the complete <a href="/wiki/Mystic_chord" title="Mystic chord">mystic chord</a> spelled in fourths (mm. 264 and 268). Jim Samson<sup id="cite_ref-Samson_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Samson-16"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup> points out that it fits in well with Scriabin's predominantly dominant quality sonorities and harmony as it may take on a dominant quality on C or F<span class="music-symbol" style="font-family: Arial Unicode MS, Lucida Sans Unicode;">‚ôØ</span>. This tritone relationship between possible resolutions is important to Scriabin's harmonic language, and it is a property shared by the <a href="/wiki/Augmented_sixth_chord#French_sixth" title="Augmented sixth chord">French sixth</a> (also prominent in his work).</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Recordings">Recordings</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Piano_Sonata_No._5_(Scriabin)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Recordings">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>This is Scriabin's most recorded sonata. Pianist <a href="/wiki/Sviatoslav_Richter" title="Sviatoslav Richter">Sviatoslav Richter</a> described it as the most difficult piece in the entire piano repertory, along with Franz Liszt's Mephisto Waltz No.1.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17"><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Notable recordings include those by <a href="/wiki/Alexei_Sultanov" title="Alexei Sultanov">Alexei Sultanov</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vladimir_Ashkenazy" title="Vladimir Ashkenazy">Vladimir Ashkenazy</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vladimir_Horowitz" title="Vladimir Horowitz">Vladimir Horowitz</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sviatoslav_Richter" title="Sviatoslav Richter">Sviatoslav Richter</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vladimir_Sofronitsky" title="Vladimir Sofronitsky">Vladimir Sofronitsky</a>, <a href="/wiki/Michael_Ponti" title="Michael Ponti">Michael Ponti</a>, <a href="/wiki/Samuil_Feinberg" title="Samuil Feinberg">Samuil Feinberg</a>, <a href="/wiki/Glenn_Gould" title="Glenn Gould">Glenn Gould</a>, <a href="/wiki/Marc-Andr%C3%A9_Hamelin" title="Marc-Andr√© Hamelin">Marc-Andr√© Hamelin</a>, Bernd Glemser and <a href="/wiki/Igor_Zhukov" title="Igor Zhukov">Igor Zhukov</a>.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Piano_Sonata_No._5_(Scriabin)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: decimal;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">She would give birth to their son <a href="/wiki/Julian_Scriabin" title="Julian Scriabin">Julian</a> on February 1908.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Nowadays Avenue de la Harpe 14.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">According to Bowers, this theme is related to the piece "Fragilit√©," Op.51 No.1, which acts as a preliminary study.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Known sketches according to Rubcova: Three leaves in two different notebooks from the years 1905 and 1906. Moscow, Glinka-Museum, Fond 31, nos. 92 and 93. Two leaves, probably from the year 1907. Moscow, Glinka-Museum, Fond 31, no. 21</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Not to be confused with his <a href="/wiki/Symphony_No._4_(Scriabin)" title="Symphony No. 4 (Scriabin)" class="mw-redirect">Symphony No. 4 "Poem of Ecstasy"</a>, Op. 54.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Scriabin wrote a doube barline between mm. 46 and 47, thus clearly marking this as a separate section from the exposition.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">According to Samson, in Sonata No. 6 and Sonata No. 7, formal tensions are created by the absence of harmonic contrast and "between the cumulative momentum of the music, usually achieved by textural rather than harmonic means, and the formal constraints of the tripartite mould."</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Not including passing notes that create circumstantial consonant harmonies, arpeggiations, broken chords (i.e. a dissonant chord broken into consonant subsets) or inversions. There is no consonant tonic chord.</span></li>
</ol>
</div>
